column1: When will 600 million people in India have received at least one dose of a COVID-19 vaccine?
column5: ['Before 1 September 2021', 'Between 1 September 2021 and 24 September 2021', 'Between 25 September 2021 and 18 October 2021', 'Between 19 October 2021 and 11 November 2021', 'Not before 12 November 2021']
column6: ['Technology', 'Society', 'Health']
Reached the target.
They are having The World's Largest Vaccination Driveon 14.09.2021, and with that number estimated for the first dose, would still take time to administrate.
Now at 603.6M. I'm sure this question will be closed imminently.

As of September 18th, 2021, Our World In Data ran by the University of Oxford estimated that roughly 594,205,296 million people in India have at least received one dose of the COVID-19 vaccination. That number is up from 586,105,233 from September 17th, 2021. That is a 11,100,063 million number increase. With this information, I would forecast that by 9/21/2021 India will reach at least 600 million of their citizens having at least 1 dose of the COVID-19 Vaccination.

I refer to „ https://ourworldindata.org/covid-vaccinations?country=IND“. 09.08.21 ≈ 400 millions 1. dose; 08.09.21 ≈ 543 mil. 1. dose; 543-400 ≈ 143 1. dose by 30 days; 143 / 30 ≈ 4.76 mil. doses / day ; 600-543 = 57 mil. / 4.76 mil. / day ≈ 12 days ; 9. Sep + 12 days = 21. September. I expect that 600 millions Indians will have been given first dose by 21. September 2021 due to statistical data due to source above.

The manufacturing, supply and distribution issues suffered by India seem more likely to ease than to worsen over time, partly through initiatives such as CEPI (Coalition for Epidemic Preparedness Innovations) aiding COVAX rollout, but also as the wealthier countries increase their own immunity levels they seem more able to recognise all the associated benefits of helping other nations with their own vaccine rollouts. The highest month for India to date looks like June at ~105M doses, and recent weeks look to be approaching this level again. I'm assuming a marginal increase over the next month being maintained into September, but allowing for it to increase a little more quickly towards October if bottlenecks improve, resulting in 460-465M end of August, and 565-595M by end of September.

Opening forecast

In order to answer this question, we can look toward other nations that have similar economies and similar population densities as India, such as Brazil. For Brazil, it seems as if their rate has almost quadratically increased, which is close to the structure at the beginning of the logistic curve. A logistic curve is generally used to model the spread of a disease (see SIR models), and seems reasonable here since although there is an acceleration of vaccines at the beginning, but will slow down near the end due to less people available to vaccinate, and the accessibility issues.

Current situation = 321.89 mill; vaccination rate ~ 3.26mill/day. This has been stable for last month and is reasonably linear. Gap = 278 mill / 3.26 mill/day = 85 days Forecast date to reach 600 mill is 2021/07/18 + 85 days = 2021/10/21

They're doing a little more than a 100 million a month currently. According to other sources I think they have the supply to keep that trend going or even increase it soon. Currently around 316 million, so the trend would put them hitting 600 million in 2.5 months or so, so end of September or early October. So I'm focusing on the middle bucket with plenty of probability given to the later buckets since 600 million is around 63% of the adult population so vaccine hesitancy may slow the rate.
18JUL - 321 pace 3/day 18 OCT

Mean Vaccination rate in July (1st to 16th) is 2,461,494 with a std dev of 178,232. If nothing changes, applying 2 sigma confidence interval, there is a 97% probability to reach 600 Mn single dose vaccinations between 24th October 2021 and 27th November 2021. Even this rate is on average reducing by ~23k fewer first doses per day

Based on the 30 days up to July 14, 600M would be reached on Oct. 2. Vaccine administration has been erratic due to supply shortages but has generally been increasing. If vaccine administration increases by an average of 11% over the next 2.5 months, 600M will be reached by Sept. 24. I am assigning a high probability to bin 2 and a low probability to bin 4 because I think improvements in increasing vaccine supplies, on average, will be more likely than more severe delays.

318,665,226 As of July 17. ~2.85M/day at 7 day avg. 7 day avg has been erratic over the last month ranging between 5.5M on June 26 and 2.6M on July 6, which would seem to confirm supply issues. "Manish Sisodia, the deputy chief minister of Delhi, tweeted that “vaccines have run out in Delhi again. The central government gives vaccines for a day or two, then we have to keep the vaccine centres closed for several days.” https://www.theguardian.com/world/2021/jul/13/india-covid-vaccine-rollout-hit-by-hesitancy-and-supply-snags. It seems at present no more than ~3M/day (1st dose) can be credibly expected with intermittent surges, so I'm thinking 3.5-3.7M as a trend over the term of the question? "In June, the federal government told the Supreme Court that 1.35 billion doses will become available between August and December." https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-56345591 This sounds plausible but I think it should be taken with a grain of salt.

Current first-dose rates won't hit the target until mid November. I guess a ramp-up is possible, but also disruptions/supply chain issues seem equally (if not more) likely, given how rollouts have gone worlwide.

Line draws to 2021-09-24 and 600 million. We can basically discount it coming in before then given how well it matches the curve and how these curves tend to turn in a sideways direction above 40% of the population. Adding some slight hedge in case it overshoots.

600M => 44% of population. Not likely to hit vaccine hesitancy by then. In the US, people with at least one dose started to slow down a bit after 40%, and the rate slowed very slightly after 40% in Germany, but to my knowledge, no other country has slowed down before somewhere between 45% to 62% was reached. 108M more people have received at least one dose in the past 30 days, or an average of 3.60M/day. Total currently at 313.5M, as of July 14. One would hope that vaccination could proceed at at least the current pace, if not faster. At the same average pace as that seen in the last month, 600M would be reached in ((600M-313.5M)/3.60M) days = 79.6 days => October 2. I will be optimistic that 600M will likely be reached a bit before that.

Took the vaccination rate from https://ourworldindata.org/covid-vaccinations, extrapolated using a simple polynomial trend line. Suggests hitting 600 million between 24th September and 1st October. Limited medical and broader infrastructure in developing countries probably constrains the more rapid vaccine roll-out seen in developed economies, though it's feasible. There continues to be global support for broadening out the roll-out and India has vaccine production in-country.

Last million took 25 days, average of 4 mil per day. This would get us to 25th September is. Last 2 weeks have a higher average than month so there is potential to speed up. Giving outcomes a higher probability because of the need to scale up. Achieving outcome1 would require 6m per day which might be a difficult increase to manage, particularly with additional 2nd doses.
